    # [Scene: Municipal Hall (Closed Negotiations) | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid, hopeful strings underlaid with a steady percussive heartbeat]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Muffled city rain, the low hum of HVAC, the shuffle of papers]
    "You sit at the head of the table as if you grew roots into the wood; your compass hangs warm against your sternum. Across from you, Eloise's posture is model-perfect—controlled, practiced. Samira stands at Eloise's shoulder"
    "like a hinge: supportive, strained, her expression a complex map you cannot fully read. Rosa and Kai sit shoulder-to-shoulder, weathered and steady. Ibe's fingers drum the tabletop once, twice—methodical."
    "The leaked documents are between you and Eloise, but they're not what they were in public; their teeth are sharper now, pared down and used as tools. You are not shouting them into the square. You"
    "used them when you had to—quietly, legally, a private lever under the Hall's polished floorboards."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We've worked the numbers again. There is a technical way to fold your barrier into modular revetments, tidal marsh buffers, and retained neighborhoods. The draft in your packet includes enforceable oversight: community seats, binding timelines, and clawbacks for displacement."
    show eloise_varela at right:
        zoom 0.7

    eloise_varela "Binding oversight. You use that word like it's a lever that turns in the right direction."
    "(She taps the projection with a pen, and a section of the map blinks.)"
    show samira_chen at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samira_chen "They also want legality. If the community oversight clause is codified with legal teeth—statutory review periods, veto rights on displacement orders—then that changes investor risk profiles. It needs clear metrics."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Metrics that mean people can stay. Flood attenuation goals, maintenance schedules tied to community crews—paying locals to maintain, not to abandon."
    "You breathe in the smell of warm paper and rain and something metallic—expectation again, but it tastes less like threat now and more like a tide turning."

    eloise_varela "If we include community seats, the investors could pull. They'll demand alternative assurances."
    hide mara_lin
    show rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "Then hold the investors accountable the way you hold contracts—with penalty clauses. Make the profit contingent on the flats staying. Tie payouts to the survival of neighborhoods, Eloise. Or we will make that bottom line the public argument."
    hide eloise_varela
    show kai_moreno at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_moreno "And while you're doing that, remember how mad the market will be if you don't get us a festival permit for this month. People celebrate survival here. It's cathartic. It makes a case in the open."

    samira_chen "We can draft the oversight framework now. I can hold it in committee as an emergency ordinance with sunset clauses that only lengthen if the metrics are met. We can attach injunctive relief for impacted households. We can also set mandatory funds for buy-in of marshkeepers—paid labor for those who maintain cordgrass buffers."
    "The room tightens; every head turns, small micro-concessions visible in the set of someone’s shoulders, a nod, a swallowed reply. Ibe's eyes find yours, bright with something like relief and a flash of grief that you both have known too long: the grief that this might finally work."
    hide samira_chen
    show mara_lin at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We don't want the entire stretch preserved at the cost of the people. We want to make the landscape resilient and the people sovereign in it. If the ordinance forces investor payouts to be tied to neighborhood survival metrics, and if community crews are funded and trained immediately, we minimize displacement."
    "Eloise sits back, fingers steepled. For a moment she looks like the planner she was before power hardened her edges—someone who wanted to build cities for people."
    hide rosa_alvarez
    show eloise_varela at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eloise_varela "If we write the clause so the city can withhold development parcels until community stewardship is demonstrably functioning, tie the barrier construction into a pilot with independent auditors, and create an emergency fund for temporarily housing affected residents within the city's own properties—then we might have a workable hybrid."
    "Samira's tablet blooms into a stream of amendments—text, clauses, bullet points. She looks at you, and though the expression on her face is complex, she gives a micro-nod: yes, we will do it (and yes, we owe a debt to whoever convinced Eloise to see the pressure differently)."
    "You and Eloise volley—one sentence, then another. Negotiation sharpens into collaboration. Rosa and Kai push particularities: worker pay scales, a clause to prioritize neighbors for temporary housing, timelines that prevent instant eviction. Ibe adds engineering constraints and maintenance budgets that make the plan realistic rather than idealistic."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We can commission community-built modular revetments. They don't have to be ornamental; they have to work fast. Patchwork plus marsh buffers. We train crews from the Flats—pay them through the ordinance. It's a plan people own."
    "Eloise studies the wording for a long time. Rain breaks hard against the skylight and the sound fills a space that had been sharp with argument. When she speaks, it is quieter—less polished, more honest."

    eloise_varela "I'm not proud of all the corners I cut. But...if these clauses are enforceable, if auditor independence is written in, and if there's a clause that guarantees the residents a majority on the oversight board for the first five years—I'll sign."
    "Her voice cracks at 'sign' and Samira is the first to reach for a pen."
    hide kai_moreno
    hide mara_lin
    hide eloise_varela

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A sudden burst of rain followed by a hush in the room; then the soft scrape of pens and the tap of a stamp]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells into a bright, emphatic chord]
    "You realize you are laughing—small, incredulous, teary. Ibe's laugh mixes with yours; Rosa puts a rough palm to your back. Kai howls something that is half curse and half cheer."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Make sure the pilot includes a clause for community-led marsh restoration—from day one. No delays."
    show samira_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samira_chen "I'll file the emergency ordinance now; I have contacts on the committee. We can call for a quick legislative session by tomorrow afternoon. Auditor names will be included; we'll select from a pre-vetted pool."
    show eloise_varela at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eloise_varela "Then let's get it written."
    "You sign. Eloise signs. Samira signs. Others sign. The table clears and the map's orange edge—once a threat—becomes a line people drew together."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse | Dusk]
    hide mara_lin
    hide samira_chen
    hide eloise_varela

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Lively, breathless acoustic guitar with rising violin]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Misting pumps, distant crowd preparations, soft laughter]
    "You climb the narrow stair to the rooftop greenhouse with Ibe at your shoulder. The air smells like wet soil and citrus—clean and immediate. Hands still slightly trembling, you brush dirt from your palms onto your"
    "trousers. The adrenaline from the Hall is receding into something livelier: the real work begins now, and it's filled with people you love."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "You did it. You pushed them hard where it mattered. You made them see the cost."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We did it together. You—"
    "(You pause, because 'you' has so many anchors: Ibe's steady hands, Samira's legal thrum, Rosa's memory) '—you helped me say the words that would stick.'"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "—would you want to— Not with signatures but...us. Something small?"
    "Your chest opens, a sudden bright ache. This is the point where danger and joy braided together can break someone open into truth."

    menu:
        "Take his hand and kiss him now on the rooftop":
            "You close the distance. The kiss is quick at first, then very long—salt-air and soil and hot relief. The greenhouse hums and a fan stutters as if applauding."
        "Laugh and promise to wait until the festival so the town can see":
            "You grin and squeeze his hand; the plan will be public, and your promise will be shared. Ibe's face settles into something both playful and proud."
        "Give him the compass—symbolically, as a pledge you'll both keep navigating together":
            "You slide the brass compass into his palm. He stares at it, thumb tracing the engraving, then looks up; there is a soft agreement in his eyes that doesn't need words."

