    "Continue to the following narration where Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq responds after your small, chosen ceremony."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Whatever we choose now—public or private—make it real. I'm done waiting to be ready while everything else collapses. I'm ready to be messy and fragile with you."
    "You laugh, and it's the kind of laugh that unknots things. You tell him, and he tells you. Words are small compared to what you both did in the Hall, but in the greenhouse they have"
    "room to be large-claim promises. You talk about small things—where you'll plant the first shared herb box, which festivals you'll never miss, how you'll schedule shifts for community crews—before the conversation slides (as it always does)"
    "down to the weightier promises: to show up for each other when storms come, to keep the other from leaving when fear suggests it."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We should tell Rosa first. And Kai. Then Samira. Then the market. Make it a thing people can cheer for."

    mara_lin "Then let's do that. Make space for a celebration. Let people see what partnership looks like when it's for the whole town."
    # [Scene Transition: Harbor Market Festival | Night]
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Drums, brass, a chorus of voices; the sound is triumphant and raw]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Firepit crackle, laughter, children running, a cheer that ripples like surf]
    "The festival is an act of defiance and repair. People trade food and stories; a kid with a face painted like a marsh heron squeals as she runs past. You stand at the edge of the"
    "stage with Ibe, Rosa at your left, Kai already orchestrating the crowd's rhythm with a grin and a cupped hand that commands attention."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Tonight we celebrate something we fought for together. Not a shield that lets us forget, but a plan that makes us builders of our future."
    "Cheers swell. You can see Samira in the crowd—she meets your eyes and gives you a small, almost-fierce smile that speaks of late nights and legal clauses."
    show samira_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samira_chen "Auditors confirmed. Ordinance passed emergency session. Oversight board confirmed—community majority for five years."
    "The crowd roars. You let that noise wash through you like a warm tide."
    show eloise_varela at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eloise_varela "We were given two choices: a fast fix or a just fix. Tonight the city chose just. Thank you—to those who would not settle, and to those who learned to listen."
    "The applause is huge. Lanterns bob like bioluminescence. You smell roasting fish and sweet dough, salt and spices, the earth-sweet scent of new plantings. Memory folds into the present: your mother teaching you to mend nets, Rosa teaching seedlings to take root, the Flats' mud under your nails."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "I promised I'd stand with you. I meant it for the Flats, and I mean it for you."
    "Your chest thuds against your ribs with something that is equal parts terror and joy. He shifts and kneels slightly—not to propose in the old way, but to make a public vow suited to this town."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Mara and I are committing—to each other and to this work. We will share labor, pay, nights off, and the seed box. We will show up. We will hold each other accountable."
    "Rosa's clap is a thunderclap. Kai's voice goes hoarse cheering. Around you, people clap and whistle, some wiping their eyes. For an instant, everything narrows to the outline of your two hands clasped together on that stage."

    mara_lin "We promise transparency. We promise labor that pays. And we promise love that is not a bargain for safety—it's a companion for the long work ahead."
    "The crowd lifts lanterns and the light spills over the water in a slow, glittering procession. A band strikes up a march that is part sea-shanty, part rallying cry. The ordinance projection rolls on the side"
    "of the stage—clauses for oversight, maintenance funds, prioritized housing assistance—legal language that now reads like a guarantee."

    "You walk down from the stage into the crowd. People press forward to shake your hand, to hug you, to say the name of a street that this ordinance saved. A woman you don't know grips your arm and says, voice thick with gratitude" "You kept our block. You kept our home."
    "You look at Ibe. He is laughing until tears track salt from his cheeks. There is a current running under the celebration—joy braided tightly with the memory of what could have been lost. Tonight it hasn't"
    "been lost, not wholly. There are repairs to make, budgets to find, nights you'll be wet and tired and aching. But there is a shape now—law, labor, love—that will hold while you all work."
    hide mara_lin
    hide samira_chen
    hide eloise_varela

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Climactic swell—strings, chorus, drums—then a soft settling cadence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The crowd singing a chorus you know; the sea answering faintly beyond the quay]
    "You reach into your pocket and find your mother's compass warm as ever. You slide a finger along the engraving—two initials scratched into brass. You think of the Flats, of Rosa's hands, of all the people"
    "who stayed awake to stitch a small world back together. You think of the promise you've just made—not only to Ibe but to the town, and how the town will now hold you to it."
    "You raise your free hand and join the song. The night is noisy and clean. The ordinance will need defenders and the marsh will need hands; storms will come again. But there is a difference now: the difference between being subject to plans and being authors of them."

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle diminuendo into a lullaby of community voices]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant slap of waves, the steady murmur of contented crowds]
    "You stand in the center of celebration—exhausted, elated, steady. Ibe leans his head against your shoulder. Rosa squeezes your fingers. Kai hands you a paper crown made of market flyers, grinning like a ridiculous hero."
    "You have brokered a hard, binding accord. You have kept the Flats. You have gained something tender and public in the middle of it. The arc that began with mud and seedlings and worry ends tonight in lantern light and loud, human joy."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse (Later that Night) | Night]

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft, intimate piano with a single violin line]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant echo of the market's final laughs, a pair of boots on the wet stair]

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We did it. We actually did it."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We did. And we will do it again, every day. There will be hard nights."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Good. Then we'll keep waking up together."
    "You let the idea settle like a seed in warm soil. He reaches into his pocket and pulls out something small: he had the compass with him, its brass catching the moon. He hands it to you—this time, he wants parity, a token of shared navigation."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Keep it. Or split it between us—wear half, wear a seam. We'll find a way."
    "You smile, and it is the sort of smile that is both answer and vow. He leans in. The greenhouse hazes around you like a promise."
